LOCAL HISTORY
AND GENEALOGY

Scene on Lenox Avenue looking north from 134th Street in the heart of the Negro Colony, New York City. Many of the buildings are owned and practically all are tenanted by colored residents.
1921 Paul Thompson, photographer
In the heart of the Negro district in New York City. Looking north on Lenox Avenue from 134th Street, 1921 Paul Thompson, photographer

45-31 West 134th Street, north side, between Lenox and Fifth Aves. The brick buildings are Public Baths maintained by the City of New York.

August 1, 1932.

P.L. Sperr.

West 134th Street, west of Lenox Avenue, showing Harlem living conditions. Several of the tenements on this block have been demolished. Others are vacated and boarded up. The buildings individually shown are in this block tho nearer to Seventh Avenue. Additional items of this character are to be found in the pamphlet published by the donor; " Why Abandoned Buildings Should Be Demolished".
